TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 


Let \[p(x) = 2x^3+3x^2+4x+5.\]

$BR
As discussed in class, \(p(2)\) can be computed via synthetic division by
filling in for the letters \(a\) through \(g\) in the table

\[\begin{array}{cccc}
2 & 3 & 4 & 5 \\
  & b & d & f \\
a & c & e & g \\
\end{array}
\]

where


$BR
\{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=a\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp( 2));


TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR
 \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=b\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp( 4));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR
  \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=c\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp( 7));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR
  \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=d\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(14));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR
  \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=e\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(18));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR
  \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=f\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(36));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR
  \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=g\).
$BR
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(41));


TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
Moreover,
\(p(2) =\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} and
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(41));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
\(p(x)\) can be written as
\[p(x) = (x-2)q(x) + r \]
where 
$BR
\(q(x) =\) \{ ans_rule(20) \} is a quadratic polynomial and
EOT
ANS(fun_cmp("2*x*x+7*x+18", limits=>[[1,2]], vars=>["x"]));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR
\(r=\)  \{ ans_rule(20) \} is a real number.
EOT


ANS(num_cmp(41));




SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT')); 
$BR $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Our matrix becomes

\[\begin{array}{cccc}
2 & 3 & 4 & 5 \\
  & 4 & 14 & 36 \\
2 & 7 & 18 & 41 \\
\end{array}
\]

Thus \[p(x) = (x-2)(2x^2+7x+18) +41\]
and \(p(2) = 41\).



EOT



